**Want me to give you a 3-line cheat sheet for editing commits (amend, reword, squash) as part of Git intermediate?**
The command:

```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
```

**Sets your identity for Git commits on your system.**

---

### **What Does It Do?**

* Every Git commit stores the **author’s name and email** in its metadata.
* This command tells Git what to use for the `Author:` field when you commit.

---

### **Breaking It Down:**

* **`git config`** – Command to set Git configuration.
* **`--global`** – Applies the setting to **all repositories** on your machine.
* **`user.name`** – Your display name for commits.
* **`user.email`** – Your email address for commits.

---

### **Example:**

```bash
git config --global user.name "Himanshu Bhandary"
git config --global user.email "himanshu@example.com"
```

Now when you commit:

```
Author: Himanshu Bhandary <himanshu@example.com>
```

---

### **Check Your Config:**

```bash
git config --list
```

This will show:

```
user.name=Himanshu Bhandary
user.email=himanshu@example.com
```

---

### **Repository-Specific Config**

If you want a different name/email just for one repo:

```bash
git config user.name "Other Name"
git config user.email "other@example.com"
```

(Without `--global`.)

